title: For Sale:  Colt Model 1860 Army Revolver
postcontent:
This Colt Model 1860 Army revolver was percussion fired six shooter, .44 caliber, manufactured by Colt Firearms, Hartford Connecticut.  Standard design employed round barrel, creeping style loading lever, barrel and cylinder held in place and easily removed for loading by releasing removable wedge, three screws, rounded cylinder with notches, brass trigger guard, iron back strap with notch for engaging shoulder stock, walnut grips.  

The top of barrel is marked " - ADDRESS  COL. SAML COLT NEW - YORK U. S. AMERICA -" although visible the marking was partially defaced at some time in the past.  Left frame is marked "COLTS / PATENT".  Cylinder is marked "COLTS PATENT No. XXXX (last four digits of serial number) / PAT. SEPT 10TH 1850", and a Texas Naval battle scene which is usually very weak but is visible on this revolver at 20%-30%.  Additional Inspector marks, cartouches on both grips appear to be “JT” (John Taylor) inspector, "H" on trigger guard, "B" on barrel under loading lever, and Greek symbols “ØØ” on the cylinder.   Matching serial numbers, 55XXX, appear underneath on both sections of frame (full S/N), trigger guard (partial S/N with some defacing), backstrap (full S/N), cylinder (partial S/N).The serial number indicates production during 1862. Serial numbers have been photo shopped out of the photos for security but are definitely there. 

The metal appearance is pleasing with smooth grey patina. The wood grips are solid with usual dings and scratches from use and what seems to be the name J.H. Croger carved in the bottom of the grips. The mechanics are fully functional. It has an 8” barrel with a good bore that shows rifling and minor pitting. The barrel is an overall dark brown and gray patina with minor oxidation. The cylinder has a similar patina. The three screw frame is a mottled silvery and brown case-hardened patina. The backstrap has a case-hardened patina. 

The Colt 1860 It was used as a side arm by cavalry, infantry, artillery troops, and naval forces. Model 1860 Army revolvers purchased by government services had brass trigger guards as does this one and civilian versions had silver plated trigger guards.  The time frame for production is correct, the finish of the gun is correct, and the presence of inspectors’ marks lend credence to this revolver being an original Colt manufactured piece in service during the Civil War and a desirable wartime example of the Colt Model 1860 Army.

Included is the original rare left handed holster in good condition with the leather still flexible.

Additional photos can be viewed by copying and pasting:

into your browser.

Lee 223 Factory Crimp Die crimps the bullet in place more firmly than any other tool. Tests demonstrate that even bullets which have no crimp groove will shoot more accurately. A firm crimp improves accuracy because pressure must build to a higher level before the bullet begins to move. This higher start pressure insures a more uniform pressure curve and less velocity variation.

The Lee Precision Factory Crimp Die is designed to give reloaders the perfect crimp on each round of reloaded ammunition. The Factory Crimp Die crimps the bullet more firmly in place than any other die with more uniform pressure. The Factory Crimp Die features a collet that squeezes the case mouth into the crimping groove for a firm hold.
